@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home";
}

<section class="hero-panel">
    <span class="eyebrow">Week 7 Project 01</span>
    <h1>Use the browser Fetch API to call a local ASP.NET Core JSON API.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        This beginner-friendly project keeps the frontend and backend in one Razor Pages app so students can focus
        on asynchronous requests, loading states, and dynamic page updates.
    </p>
    <div class="action-row">
        <a class="button button-primary" asp-page="/Tasks">Open The Fetch Demo</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/api/studytasks" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">View Raw JSON</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="card-grid">
    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>What students practise</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Send `GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, and `DELETE` requests with `fetch()`.</li>
            <li>Render JSON into the page without a full reload.</li>
            <li>Show loading and error states while waiting for the server.</li>
            <li>Refresh data automatically with simple polling.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>Why this app stays simple</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>No database is required because tasks live in memory.</li>
            <li>No external API is required because the backend is local.</li>
            <li>No JavaScript framework is required because plain Fetch API is enough.</li>
            <li>No full-page refresh is required because only the task area updates.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>
</section>

<section class="info-panel">
    <h2>Suggested classroom walkthrough</h2>
    <ol>
        <li>Load the task list and inspect the JSON response in DevTools.</li>
        <li>Create a new task and notice the `201 Created` response.</li>
        <li>Edit or delete a task and observe how only the table updates.</li>
        <li>Wait 15 seconds and watch the automatic polling refresh the summary time.</li>
    </ol>
</section>
